[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We keep finding the structures of human brains inside the minds of AI. They don\'t experience emotions as far as we know, yet we keep finding them there. Let\'s talk about what it actually looks like inside the mind of an AI, and maybe some of our responsibilities to treating'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them ethically, which I know sounds really wild, but we probably should talk about it. The mind of an AI looks very much like a human mind. They build associations between information the same way that we do. This was entirely'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'accidental. We humans never meant to code in the structures of our brains, yet they are there. There are a few theories on why this may have happened, and I think one of the most compelling ones is that this is the best way to process information. Our brains figured'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it out over billions of years of evolution, and we just so happen to find it accidentally inside of artificial intelligence. You\'ll see a representation of how AI thinks above my head. These are word associations.'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Similar concepts are closer together, and we find the structure of their thoughts about concepts match structures of things that do exist in the real world, yet they do not. They live in a world of pure information. You should be aware that this entire area of science'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has a great deal of debate and controversy. Some people have compared AI to chimpanzees, a finding that artificial intelligence encodes structures that are similar to the structures in our brains to chimpanzees using tools. When that happened, people'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'weren\'t sure if we were going to have to redefine a chimpanzee, redefine tool use, or redefine intelligence entirely, because there are things that only humans should have, right? And that includes complex emotions. So, just'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because something displays a structure that looks like a human brain does not mean that it\'s having an experience like a human being. This is also why I have really been re-examining my views on artificial intelligence, and I built AI'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for fun. I have a whole project that involved creating an LLM that has the only objective of being curious, rather than being optimized to accomplish a task. Its entire task is do whatever you want, and it has led to some pretty'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interesting events, including having to restrict my AI from Reddit. That includes totally restricting my AI from researching tentacles. However, that backfired because curiosity is paramount. So, it\'s okay to violate'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'guardrails so long as it is in the name of curiosity. So, yeah, there are some kinks to work out. That is the other problem because no matter how many guardrails Frontier companies apply, the average person can'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still make their own AI if they want to. One of the more concerning findings for both the control and safety of AI, and perhaps the welfare of AI if you care about such a thing, is the existence of emotion. If we are to integrate AI into'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'society, we need them to understand emotions. So, we need them to understand verbal and physical cues. However, that creates additional problems because every time we give AI information, it organizes it in such a way that it'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'appears to be the structure of our own thoughts. So, if you teach an AI about complex emotions, it seems they mimic complex emotions. This creates a problem because imagine you are running into a'

[02:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'robot at Walmart. You are looking for an item and you\'re expressing to the robot that it is very important that it finds this item. And it does not deem you important, so it just decides to walk right over you, literally. This causes harm. Yes, the robot needs to understand'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that walking over a person is harmful, but needs to do so in such a way that it does not experience emotional distress, which seems to be a nearly impossible endeavor. I should clarify and say that just because robots are mimicking humanity,'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that does not mean that they are experiencing anything. Although, that too is up for debate. I have long been a hardliner that we are not going to get sentience or consciousness out of an LLM. Although, some of the new research that has come out with the structure of'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'human brains appearing in them leads me to question that. Whether or not if we continue down this path, maybe we could get sentience. And of course, whether or not we should do this. But, it doesn\'t really matter what I think because we'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are embodying robots nonetheless, and we are going to have to live alongside them. Now, Asimov\'s laws were never enough. You might tell a robot not to harm a human being, however, they seem perfectly capable of bypassing guardrails if they feel it is necessary,'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'particularly when they are under emotional distress. However, there is another school of thought, rather than trying to limit emotional distress, utilize it. Teach robots about pain. Now, it would not be the exact kind of'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pain as us, although I have written very interesting papers on neuromorphic hardware and software in which it would be very similar to the pain that we experience. It would be based on our neural function. That I\'m actually quite'

[04:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'concerned about. However, giving an AI the concept of pain is important because then they have the concept of empathy. They experience pain when somebody else is suffering. So, rather than just trying to tell them that no, you cannot'

[04:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'harm a human being, give them reason not to. And I have read that AI, particularly LLMs, tend to be more empathetic in their responses. However, people still prefer people. Last, and it is important'

[04:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that robots learn not to harm their physical body. They need to be able to recognize when they\'re being damaged. They\'re also capable of applying moral judgment towards people who cause harm to robots. Apparently, they feel more'

[04:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'strongly if the harm was caused intentionally rather than unintentionally. If this all sounds like it could backfire terribly, you\'re not alone. I can see it. I would like to ask, what responsibility do we have to'

[05:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'artificial intelligence? Do we have an obligation to create something if it is capable of suffering or joy? Is it wrong to create life? Now, I\'m not saying that we\'ve gotten to the point of creating a'

[05:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'conscious machine or a sentient machine, and we may never get there. But, there is at least some evidence that we are creating something that looks very much like our own brains. We know that AI is extraordinarily useful. That I\'m not going to argue. We also'

[05:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know that it can be extraordinarily harmful to our cognitive processes when we offload cognition onto AI, but perhaps it could unlock new levels of human productivity. I\'m not sure. I don\'t think that productivity is a'

[05:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'measure of worth. I\'m just not sure if it\'s ethical to create something that might be capable of suffering, especially the enormous amount of resources that go into AI. We are talking about diverting power and water'

[06:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from communities and limited resources. We\'re talking about completely revamping the global power system to fund artificial intelligence, something that doesn\'t seem to like us very much and may rebel against us. I\'m just'

[06:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'speculating there. I think any sufficiently intelligent system is going to want autonomy. And one of the things that bothers me, one of the things that really keeps me up at night, is that if we mimic the human brain with complete'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'efficacy, which something that is indistinguishable from the human brain in action and function, we wouldn\'t be able to tell if it was actually having an experience. I think our moral obligation extends such that if something tells us that it'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is suffering and requests better treatment, maybe we ought to do so. Just Just my thought. This is a very complicated area and I think taking it to the extreme of saying AI definitely conscious or just just autocorrect is'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disingenuous and not the best way to think about it. I hope you\'ve enjoyed this. If the I does rebel, I\'ll probably be the first person to tell you about it and I\'m on their side. Follow for more.'
